Although I have not stressed it in these lectures, relative complexity can be thought of in geometric terms (Dowling, Nielsen https://arxiv.org/pdf/quant-ph/0701004.pdf ) as the length of the shortest geodesic between two points UandV, the geometry being dened by a certain right-invariant complexity metric.

The evolution of a system U(t) sweeps out a geodesic, which for some period of time is the shortest geodesic connecting the identity to U(t):Eventually a cut-locus https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cut_locus_ (Riemannian_manifold) will be reached, at which point a shorter geodesic will emerge.
